title: For Sale:  Remington pre Model 11
postcontent: This is a Remington Autoloading Shotgun produced in 1907. Remington first produced this shotgun in 1905, and in 1911 would rename it the Remington Model 11. It is an American-made copy of John Moses Browning's Auto-5 ("A5"), and was made under license from FN in Belgium, who owned Browning's patent.These two models of shotgun were popular with both gangsters and the law enforcement officers who hunted them during the Depression, though both groups preferred to cut the barrel shorter than this one's original 28 inches.In the photos, you should be able to see a scratch in the receiver bluing, and a chip near the end of the forend. Also some scratches on the buttstock.This specimen has the rounded "cap" on the grip and the safety still inside the trigger guard - both of which were seen during the first few years of production only.

title: For Sale:  Springfield Model 1903
postcontent: Springfield Armory Model 1903 bolt action rifle, 30-06.From my research all of the metal on this gun apears to be correct to the 1918 period. The stock marking show it to have been rebuilt at Rock Island Arsenal sometime between 1920-30 and inspected by Frank Krack.Here are the marking I've located on the rifle:End of the barrel is marked "S A" (Springfield Armory), below that is the "Bomb" mark and below that is 1-18 for 01/1918. Saferty lug marked "l ll". Smooth trigger, not serrated.Front sling loop marked with a "U".Bayonet lug marked with an "H" Stock has several marking, two "P" stamps behind trigger indicating it was rebuilt at one point. Above the trigger is stamped "RIA" with "FK" under it inside a box. This is to show it was rebuilt at Rock Island Arsenal and inspected by Frank Krack between 1920 & 1930.Faintly under this I can make out a different marking that looks to be "C.E.(maybe B)T. over "RIA" with a box around it. I can not find any info on this marking. To the right are the initials, "E L J" in a box. I've not found any info on this marking either.To the left of all of this there is stamped "7K". I can't find any info on this either.After very close inspection I see the number "78" between the trigger and the "P" proof mark in the stock. I cannot find any info on this either.If anyone has info on the unknown marking it would be appreciated.$675.00

title: For Sale:  Beretta model 686 Silver Pigeon 12 gauge
postcontent: This auction is for a Beretta Model 686 Silver Pigeon over under shotgun in 12 gauge. It is built around the best-in-class 686 action, which is compact and low-profile while being extremely strong. The Optima-Bore, Optima-Choke barrels are light-weight and place the shotgun’s point of balance right at the hinge-pin, meaning lively feel in the hands and natural point ability. And with its select-walnut stock and tasteful scroll engraving, the Silver Pigeon I Sporting won’t fail to turn heads at the range, also thanks to its unmistakable Beretta looks. At the heart of the Silver Pigeon I Sporting is the legendary 686 action, a long-standing favorite among competition shooters and hunters.The 686 receiver vault-like locking strength while keeping the profile considerably lower. The advantage is that the eye of the shooter is a lot closer to the plane of his supporting hand: considerably better swing and hand-eye coordination, more targets. Another advantage of the Silver Pigeon action is the fact that the locking lugs are conical. As the number of shots fired goes into the five digits, the receiver will still lock up positively: the conical lugs merely “self-adjust” by setting themselves slightly deeper into the barrel unit, without any compromise on strength. This means that the Silver Pigeon Sporting is a shotgun that will stand up to years of enjoyment and can be passed down from generation to generation. The oil-finished stock sports a beautiful and crisp checkering pattern, and the schnabel fore-end adds to the classic flavor of this over-under. The scroll-engraved receiver is a functional work of art in itself, with its interesting geometry blending perfectly with the stock and contributing to the gun’s graceful lines. This is a shotgun that has all the elements of a treasured heirloom, without the price-tag to match. This is a excellent shooter with almost perfect feel when throwing it up to shoot and will be a excellent addition to your collection or for the more serious shooter. If you have any questions feel free to call or E-mail us.
